JEREMY: Is that
a slow

48:56.080 --> 48:58.800
Oh, no, you're building up
speed as you cross the line.

48:58.840 --> 49:00.440
Come on, Kevin!

49:00.480 --> 49:02.280
JEREMY: Ooh, that's
a determined-looking face.

49:02.320 --> 49:03.880
Clipping the corner,

49:03.920 --> 49:06.200
but keeping two wheels
on the track, nice to see.

49:06.240 --> 49:08.600
Yes, you've done what I do.
You brake there

49:08.640 --> 49:10.160
and then you've got
a slingshot

49:10.200 --> 49:12.280
into what we're calling
the Difficult Bit.

49:12.320 --> 49:14.640
That's when it goes
really skatey as you...

49:14.680 --> 49:16.160
You've really gotta pay...

49:16.200 --> 49:17.800
Ooh, I say,
that's rather good.

49:17.840 --> 49:19.640
For a man who grew up
with a Pulsar.

49:19.680 --> 49:22.480
Kevin, you absolute numpty!

49:22.520 --> 49:25.160
JEREMY: Right, oh, look at
that, it's got the tail out.

49:25.200 --> 49:27.480
KEVIN: Yeah, got the tail
out, got him going good.

49:27.520 --> 49:29.080
JEREMY:
Traction control saved it,

49:29.120 --> 49:31.920
now you can floor it
through to Difficult Bit 2.

49:33.880 --> 49:35.480
KEVIN: Oh, she's going
all right.
-Nicely done.

49:35.520 --> 49:37.120
-That was tough.
-Yeah.

49:37.160 --> 49:39.360
JEREMY: It is a tough bit.
This is really slippery

49:39.400 --> 49:40.880
when you come back
on the Tarmac,

49:40.920 --> 49:42.320
you think that's OK,
and it isn't.

49:44.400 --> 49:46.240
Tyres being
absolutely tortured,

49:46.280 --> 49:47.560
that's looking nice.

49:47.600 --> 49:49.040
Right, onto the straight.

49:49.080 --> 49:51.320
Come on, baby!
Come on, baby!

49:51.360 --> 49:54.480
JEREMY: It's more exciting
than cricket, way more!

49:54.520 --> 49:56.280
As is being asleep.

49:56.320 --> 49:58.160
Were you flat-out
through there?

49:58.200 --> 50:00.200
KEVIN: I was flat-out
through there, then
I messed this up.

50:00.240 --> 50:01.800
JEREMY: Ooh! I'm not...

50:01.840 --> 50:03.440
KEVIN: Yeah, I messed it up,
I missed the curve.

50:03.480 --> 50:04.880
Ballsy flat-out through there,

50:04.920 --> 50:06.960
but you crossed the line,
you did it.

50:08.080 --> 50:10.360
I got it. Time?

50:11.520 --> 50:12.400
So...

50:13.720 --> 50:15.600
Time?

50:15.640 --> 50:17.160
-Patience.

50:17.200 --> 50:19.680
You're a cricketer,
we know you have patience.

50:19.720 --> 50:20.960
OK.

50:21.000 --> 50:22.880
Because what else
is there to have?

50:22.920 --> 50:24.880
-It wasn't bad.
-No, it looked OK.

50:24.920 --> 50:26.480
-Brian.
-Yes.

50:28.120 --> 50:30.680
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

50:30.720 --> 50:32.120
Come on, let's see Brian's.

50:33.920 --> 50:35.360
KEVIN: Oh.

50:35.400 --> 50:37.240
JEREMY: Right, no creeping
across the line.

50:37.280 --> 50:41.160
And here we go! Yee!

50:41.200 --> 50:43.840
JEREMY: That is a colourful
comb... That's a...

50:43.880 --> 50:46.960
Cheat. He's cheating! Cheat!

50:47.000 --> 50:48.680
He's a cheat!

50:48.720 --> 50:52.200
JEREMY: It's not
Formula One,

50:52.240 --> 50:55.160
we won't penalise him for
this, we have no stewards.

50:55.200 --> 50:56.480
KEVIN: Oh!

50:56.520 --> 50:58.960
JEREMY: Oh, my God!
Coming in hot!

51:00.120 --> 51:01.400
Holding it well, though,

51:01.440 --> 51:04.080
and, I must say,
that is exuberant.

51:04.120 --> 51:07.600
He's on fire!

51:07.640 --> 51:10.560
JEREMY: Into the gravel cell,
the banked gravel corner,

51:10.600 --> 51:12.600
nicely done through there.

51:12.640 --> 51:15.280
Look at those stones
coming off the back of that.

51:15.320 --> 51:16.840
Difficult Bit 2.

51:16.880 --> 51:18.960
Floor it.

51:19.000 --> 51:21.000
JEREMY: You don't think this
is gonna be slippery but it
is.

51:21.040 --> 51:22.840
Every time, that happens.

51:22.880 --> 51:24.640
Nicely held, though, Brian.

51:24.680 --> 51:26.360
You really do get around.

51:26.400 --> 51:29.720
And there he is, onto the
main straight and relaxing.

51:29.760 --> 51:31.800
Yoo!

51:31.840 --> 51:33.600
JEREMY: Well, not
completely relaxing.

51:33.640 --> 51:35.440
Were you flat through here,
as well?

51:35.480 --> 51:37.400
AUDIENCE: Ooh.

51:37.440 --> 51:39.720
BRIAN: I took it...
JEREMY: Flat-out,
that's good.

51:39.760 --> 51:40.800
Braking hard.

51:42.440 --> 51:44.160
Not bad at all.

51:44.200 --> 51:46.320
And there we are, across the
line, that's both of them.

51:55.920 --> 51:59.760
Right. Now, I've got
your times here.

51:59.800 --> 52:02.680
I'll tell you one thing,
they're very, very close.

52:02.720 --> 52:05.160
So you were kind of smooth
and crickety.

52:05.200 --> 52:08.120
-Yeah.
-You were kind of exuberant.

52:08.160 --> 52:11.280
-Yeah.
-They are ridiculously close.

52:11.320 --> 52:13.200
-OK, here we go.
-The suspense.

52:13.240 --> 52:14.520
-I mean, come on.
-Yeah.

52:14.560 --> 52:16.800
-Killing me.
-OK, Kevin.

52:18.480 --> 52:21.040
-1:17.2.

52:21.080 --> 52:23.800
So at the moment,
you're the fastest man

52:23.840 --> 52:26.840
who's ever been
round our track.

52:26.880 --> 52:28.400
-Until...
-This precise moment.

52:28.440 --> 52:30.080
Until about 30 seconds.

52:36.680 --> 52:38.000
Brian Wilson...

52:38.040 --> 52:41.880
-Ooh.
-1:17...

52:41.920 --> 52:43.800
AUDIENCE: Ooh.
-Point one.

52:43.840 --> 52:46.480
-Give it to me.
-..five.

52:46.520 --> 52:47.840
-Damn it!
-Ah!

52:47.880 --> 52:51.160
-Seriously, 0.3 of a second.

52:51.200 --> 52:52.160
Well done, sir.

52:57.160 --> 53:00.560
-That's close.
JEREMY: That is nice.

53:00.600 --> 53:02.840
That is a nice result,
I'm very pleased with that.

53:02.880 --> 53:05.960
And there we are,
you are still the fastest man

53:06.000 --> 53:07.320
who's been round our track.

53:07.360 --> 53:09.240
You have come a long way
for nothing.

53:09.280 --> 53:11.120
Thank you.

53:11.160 --> 53:13.640
JEREMY: Literally nothing...
-Much appreciated.

53:13.680 --> 53:15.800
So, honestly, I mean
it's been an absolute joy

53:15.840 --> 53:18.120
-having you both here...
-Came here for the sheep.

53:18.160 --> 53:20.040
Yeah, no, take one home.

53:20.080 --> 53:22.200
So there we are,
ladies and gentlemen,

53:22.240 --> 53:25.520
Brian Wilson, and the fastest
person who makes a living

53:25.560 --> 53:27.880
by throwing and hitting
and catching small balls,

53:27.920 --> 53:30.320
-Kevin Pietersen!

53:32.160 --> 53:33.840
KEVIN: Thank you, sir.
Thank you.

53:37.680 --> 53:38.920
Right.

53:38.960 --> 53:43.680
Now, this week
we are having a race

53:43.720 --> 53:46.840
from Central Park in New York
to Niagara Falls,

53:46.880 --> 53:49.480
and it's Jeremy
in the new Ford GT

53:49.520 --> 53:51.160
against James and me

53:51.200 --> 53:53.520
in a whole selection
of public transport.

53:53.560 --> 53:55.200
Yes, and when
we left the action,

53:55.240 --> 53:57.640
Jeremy was miles ahead
in the car,

53:57.680 --> 54:00.240
slowly going deaf
from the drone of the engine.

54:00.280 --> 54:02.960
But now we were
about to haul him in

54:03.000 --> 54:06.160
as we boarded
the flight to Buffalo.

54:15.200 --> 54:16.840
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

54:20.280 --> 54:22.360
RICHARD: Ow!
JAMES: Sorry.

54:22.400 --> 54:26.080
Get out of the way. Get out
of the way, I'm in a race.

54:27.360 --> 54:29.320
Hello. Hello.

54:29.360 --> 54:32.160
Don't get in the way
of someone

54:32.200 --> 54:35.680
who's just given up
a 43-year smoking habit.

54:35.720 --> 54:37.760
JEREMY: Meanwhile...

54:37.800 --> 54:39.240
JAMES: Has he got to go
in that?

54:39.280 --> 54:40.160
MAN: Yes.

54:43.960 --> 54:45.840
OK, see you on board.

54:48.080 --> 54:50.560
STEWARD: Welcome aboard.
-Hello. Thank you.

54:50.600 --> 54:51.560
Oh, God.

54:52.840 --> 54:54.560
Hello. Hello.

54:57.760 --> 54:59.360
Yeah.

54:59.400 --> 55:00.760
OK.

55:07.400 --> 55:10.000
JEREMY: Having covered
160 miles,

55:10.040 --> 55:14.880
the GT's tiny tank
was now nearly empty.

55:14.920 --> 55:20.280
This is a splash-and-dash.
Right, petroleum.

55:20.320 --> 55:21.560
Oh, please let it not be

55:21.600 --> 55:23.440
one of those stupid
American ones

55:23.480 --> 55:25.520
where I've gotta pay first,
I don't know how much I want.

55:28.280 --> 55:29.840
Sadly, it was.

55:29.880 --> 55:32.920
No. Not a debit card.

55:34.080 --> 55:36.040
I haven't got one... Ah.

55:39.200 --> 55:40.920
What?

55:40.960 --> 55:43.320
PA: All exits are marked
with a sign overhead...

55:43.360 --> 55:46.440
It's very unusual
having business class
at the back, isn't it?

55:46.480 --> 55:48.720
Imagine what it's like
at the front.

55:48.760 --> 55:50.520
Must be sort of like there.

55:50.560 --> 55:52.920
It's quite good if you sit at
the back in business class,

55:52.960 --> 55:54.480
survey the whole aeroplane.

55:55.840 --> 55:57.760
This is an Embraer 190.

55:57.800 --> 55:59.640
I can tell you a bit about
these actually.

55:59.680 --> 56:01.040
PA: Prepare for departure.

56:01.080 --> 56:03.720
Oh, dear, you can't,
he's talking.

56:03.760 --> 56:05.840
JEREMY: Hello. Can I...
The pump says...

56:05.880 --> 56:07.440
It's just coming up
"not approved".

56:07.480 --> 56:09.600
Does it have a chip?
It's probably the chip.

56:09.640 --> 56:11.120
How do I pay? Cos...

56:11.160 --> 56:13.040
I'll turn the pump on,
you pump what you need

56:13.080 --> 56:15.200
and I'll let you run
the card when you're done.

56:15.240 --> 56:17.520
Thank you so much.

56:17.560 --> 56:19.360
If you talk like Hugh Grant,
you can get anywhere.

56:25.800 --> 56:28.400
Any minute now, Richard
Hammond and James May

56:28.440 --> 56:31.480
will be thinking,
"Mmm, a beer, I think."

56:34.000 --> 56:36.960
Anyway, here we go,
let's catch him up.

56:37.000 --> 56:38.200
Definitely.

56:44.080 --> 56:47.200
I think we should celebrate
our progress right now,

56:47.240 --> 56:48.800
as we're moving so well.

56:48.840 --> 56:50.240
-Hello.
-Hello.

56:50.280 --> 56:52.400
JAMES: Hi.

56:52.440 --> 56:55.720
-Two beers, please.
-Let me see.

56:55.760 --> 56:57.520
So, as it turns out,

56:57.560 --> 57:00.400
unfortunately I won't be able
to serve you any beer today.

57:00.440 --> 57:02.360
Can I offer you a water,
Coke, Sprite?

57:02.400 --> 57:04.440
-No, I'm sorry.

57:04.480 --> 57:07.320
Wine. Wine? Two glasses
of wine? White wine.

57:07.360 --> 57:08.960
I'm not quite too sure why,

57:09.000 --> 57:10.760
but unfortunately
I won't be able to.

57:10.800 --> 57:12.440
Can I get you
some other beverages?

57:14.360 --> 57:17.360
JEREMY: However, while they
were squashed and thirsty,

57:17.400 --> 57:19.200
there was no getting round
the fact

57:19.240 --> 57:23.120
that they were doing 500mph,
and I wasn't.

57:25.280 --> 57:29.000
Come on, fellow Ford driver,
get out of the way, please.

57:30.320 --> 57:31.560
You've got a Ford!

57:34.400 --> 57:36.320
We are gonna be
reeling him in now.

57:36.360 --> 57:38.360
We're not gonna get stuck
behind anything.

57:38.400 --> 57:39.560
-No.
-In traffic.

57:39.600 --> 57:41.920
No. Nobody is gonna have
a puncture.

57:41.960 --> 57:43.560
Or shed the load
from a pick-up truck.

57:43.600 --> 57:44.480
No.

57:48.000 --> 57:49.840
JEREMY: My biggest problem,
though,

57:49.880 --> 57:53.720
was the woeful
lane discipline.

57:53.760 --> 57:56.480
And you're gonna stay in
that lane, are you, really?

57:58.040 --> 57:59.720
Undertaking.

57:59.760 --> 58:03.320
This is allowed in the
United States and America.

58:05.840 --> 58:10.800
You can see why. People
don't use their mirrors.

58:10.840 --> 58:12.640
It was a problem.

58:12.680 --> 58:16.480
And then there was
a bigger one.

58:16.520 --> 58:20.680
What the hell's this?
I'm in a traffic jam.

58:20.720 --> 58:24.880
A bloody traffic jam. No.

58:24.920 --> 58:27.040
PA: We're about to begin
our descent

58:27.080 --> 58:28.320
into the Buffalo airport.

58:28.360 --> 58:30.000
We'll be on the ground
shortly.

58:30.040 --> 58:31.360
Look.

58:31.400 --> 58:33.800
Is there a fat idiot
in a very fast Ford?

58:33.840 --> 58:36.080
-Nope.
-Good.

58:38.880 --> 58:40.600
Why is there a traffic jam?
And it's a bad one.

58:40.640 --> 58:41.920
Look, we're all stopped.

58:46.040 --> 58:49.240
Come on. Come on, come on.
Come on, come on, come on.

58:51.760 --> 58:54.600
Go, go, go, go, go.
Chair, please.

58:56.200 --> 58:58.040
JEREMY: Oh, shit.

59:03.720 --> 59:06.440
There we go. I'm in.

59:07.920 --> 59:12.280
Blimey! Yeah, that is...
I am safe.

59:12.320 --> 59:15.080
JEREMY: Incident.
There's been an accident.

59:15.120 --> 59:17.800
There's the problem. Jesus.

59:20.200 --> 59:23.160
We have some time to make up.

59:23.200 --> 59:26.600
Seeing an accident like that
normally slows you down,

59:26.640 --> 59:27.840
but I couldn't do that.

59:27.880 --> 59:32.120
I was upholding
the honour of the car.

59:32.160 --> 59:35.280
They should be landing
in about ten minutes.

59:37.480 --> 59:38.760
Oh, no.

59:38.800 --> 59:41.360
JEREMY: May

59:41.400 --> 59:44.440
-Yes! Yes.
-James, too loud. Too loud.

59:44.480 --> 59:46.640
-Shit.
JAMES: Where are you?

59:46.680 --> 59:49.960
I'm 130 miles from Buffalo.

59:50.000 --> 59:53.600
He's 130 miles away.

59:53.640 --> 59:55.240
Well, you better
get a move on then

59:55.280 --> 59:57.960
in your 200 and whatever
it is mile-an-hour car.

59:58.000 --> 59:59.520
I... Oh.

59:59.560 --> 1:00:01.040
JEREMY: That's...
-Keep going.

1:00:01.080 --> 1:00:03.080
Oh, for God's.... Shut up.

1:00:03.120 --> 1:00:04.400
JAMES: Bye.

1:00:04.440 --> 1:00:08.080
Right,
where do we get the bus?

1:00:08.120 --> 1:00:11.360
JAMES: We now only had a
couple of dozen miles to go.

1:00:11.400 --> 1:00:13.080
We'd catch a bus
into Buffalo

1:00:13.120 --> 1:00:14.880
and then another
to the finish line

1:00:14.920 --> 1:00:16.360
at the Niagara Falls.

1:00:19.080 --> 1:00:20.800
Trying to think
where this went wrong.

1:00:20.840 --> 1:00:23.120
George Washington Bridge,
that didn't help.

1:00:23.160 --> 1:00:26.840
The accident and the
traffic jam that resulted,
that didn't help.

1:00:26.880 --> 1:00:28.440
But I think the main problem

1:00:28.480 --> 1:00:30.960
is that Jet Blue
managed to do

1:00:31.000 --> 1:00:35.800
an hour and 15 minute flight
in an hour.

1:00:35.840 --> 1:00:37.680
RICHARD: Oh, I say.

1:00:37.720 --> 1:00:39.720
JAMES: Oh, I see,
it folds out like that?

1:00:39.760 --> 1:00:42.040
RICHARD: That's very clever.
JAMES: Here we go.

1:00:42.080 --> 1:00:44.800
RICHARD: Thank you.
JAMES: Aligned.

1:00:44.840 --> 1:00:47.040
-There's a wheelchair
section right over there.
-Thank you very much.

1:00:50.160 --> 1:00:53.280
Come on. Yay!

1:00:53.320 --> 1:00:57.360
The Trump enthusiast
has pulled over!

1:00:58.880 --> 1:01:02.160
Right, let's find out
where he is.

1:01:05.080 --> 1:01:08.160
It's Mr Bell End.
Hammond, where are you?

1:01:08.200 --> 1:01:10.720
Leaving the airport on a bus.

1:01:10.760 --> 1:01:14.200
Right. Well,
I'm 90 miles behind you.

1:01:14.240 --> 1:01:18.440
You're gonna
have to make that up
in no time.

1:01:18.480 --> 1:01:21.200
How far are you
from Niagara Falls now?

1:01:21.240 --> 1:01:23.520
23 miles.

1:01:25.120 --> 1:01:27.240
RICHARD: I'd say
you could be doomed.

1:01:27.280 --> 1:01:30.320
Good luck,
we're getting closer. Bye.

1:01:30.360 --> 1:01:31.280
He's never gonna do it.

1:01:33.320 --> 1:01:38.480
Oh! I don't want this car
to lose, I properly love it.

1:01:38.520 --> 1:01:39.920
It's just so exciting.

1:01:39.960 --> 1:01:42.560
All the things that make it
bad and annoying

1:01:42.600 --> 1:01:44.800
make it brilliant
and exciting.

1:01:44.840 --> 1:01:47.920
The noise, and the ride,
and the roughness.

1:01:47.960 --> 1:01:54.040
It's just raucous, raw,
bareback, unplugged energy.

1:01:56.520 --> 1:02:01.200
I want it to win,
I want it to beat the plane.

1:02:01.240 --> 1:02:04.560
But to do that, it
would have to do 113 miles

1:02:04.600 --> 1:02:08.360
in the time it takes a bus
to do 23.

1:02:08.400 --> 1:02:10.080
PA: Stop requested.

1:02:10.120 --> 1:02:11.200
JEREMY: Luckily, however,

1:02:11.240 --> 1:02:13.960
buses have other people
on them.

1:02:14.000 --> 1:02:16.200
JAMES: I don't like this bit.
What do you do?

1:02:16.240 --> 1:02:17.840
You just have to sit here.

1:02:17.880 --> 1:02:20.440
Yeah. Bus travel
is tricky to like, isn't it?

1:02:20.480 --> 1:02:22.320
And we've gotta stop
and change buses,

1:02:22.360 --> 1:02:25.400
and if we lose ten,
15 minutes waiting for
the next bus...

1:02:25.440 --> 1:02:27.000
I know, it's not in the bag.

1:02:29.520 --> 1:02:31.040
76 miles.

1:02:33.120 --> 1:02:34.880
PA: Stop requested.

1:02:36.120 --> 1:02:37.840
Who pulled the...

1:02:37.880 --> 1:02:42.280
Well, it is a bus with...
Can't be rude to customers.

1:02:42.320 --> 1:02:44.840
Nobody else pull the string
until we've got off, please.

1:02:44.880 --> 1:02:45.920
Let's just go all the way.

1:02:53.080 --> 1:02:55.240
Hello. Where are you?

1:02:55.280 --> 1:02:58.840
I think about 55 miles away
from the finish line.

1:02:58.880 --> 1:03:00.680
-Yeah.

1:03:00.720 --> 1:03:02.160
Right, this is
gonna be close.

1:03:02.200 --> 1:03:04.680
Have you not got
to Buffalo yet?

1:03:04.720 --> 1:03:06.520
No, no, we're in Buffalo,

1:03:06.560 --> 1:03:09.200
but we haven't got
to the bus change point.

1:03:09.240 --> 1:03:13.880
Oh, really? Oh!
Does your bus keep stopping?

1:03:13.920 --> 1:03:16.120
Well, of course it does,
it's a bloody bus!

1:03:16.160 --> 1:03:18.120
I haven't been on one
since I was eight.

1:03:18.160 --> 1:03:19.960
That kept stopping.

1:03:20.000 --> 1:03:22.280
I thought, "I won't go on
another one, they're stupid."

1:03:22.320 --> 1:03:24.040
-They're still the same.
-Bye-bye.

1:03:26.680 --> 1:03:29.520
JEREMY: Amazingly,
I was still in the running,

1:03:29.560 --> 1:03:33.600
but my furious pace meant
I had to make a decision.

1:03:33.640 --> 1:03:37.760
Do I drive like Al Gore would
want me to drive, at 55mph,

1:03:37.800 --> 1:03:39.640
and possibly make
the finish line

1:03:39.680 --> 1:03:41.040
